d of the century, when the bank and energy sectors developed political strategies to participate in financial markets. His account adopts a multilevel approach that considers the political and legal landscapes in which corporations are embedded to answer two questions: how did banks and financial firms transition from being providers of capital to financial market actors? Second, how did new organizational structures cause market participants to engage in high-risk activities? After careful historical analysis, Prechel examines how organizational and political-legal arrangements contribute to current record-high income and wealth inequality, and considers societal preconditions for change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCorporation lawzUnited States. 0aCorporationsxCorrupt practiceszUnited States. 0aCorporationsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aFinancializationzUnited States. 0aIncome distributionzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh  aBanks.  acorporate form.  acorporate political behavior.  acorporations.  afinancial wrongdoing.  afinancialization.  ainequality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361446840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503614468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503614468.jp